Note:
Asynchronous I/O — completion-style read/write layered on the event loop.

This module turns a blocking-style read or write request into a readiness-
driven, non-blocking completion. It does not re-implement polling or timers;
it builds directly on the completed epoll reactor in event_loop.runa. A caller
submits an async_read or async_write against a descriptor together with a
$name completion callback. The request is captured in an AsyncOp record, the
descriptor is placed into non-blocking mode, and the descriptor is registered
with the event loop for the readiness direction the operation needs (EPOLLIN
for reads, EPOLLOUT for writes). Control returns to the caller immediately;
the actual transfer is deferred until the kernel reports the descriptor ready.

Mechanism: when the descriptor becomes ready, the event loop invokes this
module's internal dispatcher, async_io_on_ready, passing back the AsyncOp
pointer that was handed to the loop as the user argument. The dispatcher
performs the real read or write syscall exactly once, stores the transfer
result (bytes moved, or a negative errno) on the AsyncOp, deregisters the
descriptor from the loop so the one-shot completion cannot re-fire, invokes
the caller's completion callback with the AsyncOp, and finally frees the
AsyncOp. The completion callback recovers the transferred byte count through
async_io_result before the record is reclaimed.

AsyncOp layout (64 bytes):
    offset 0:   fd            — the watched descriptor (owned by the caller)
    offset 8:   op_kind       — 0 read, 1 write
    offset 16:  buffer        — caller-owned data buffer for the transfer
    offset 24:  count         — number of bytes to read or write
    offset 32:  user_callback — $name completion fn-ptr (call_indirect_1 ABI)
    offset 40:  user_arg      — opaque argument reserved for the caller
    offset 48:  result        — bytes transferred, or negative errno
    offset 56:  loop          — the event loop this op is registered with
:End Note

Import "runtime/concurrency/async_runtime/event_loop.runa" as EL
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/platform/linux_x86_64/syscall.runa" as Sys
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/call_indirect.runa" as Call

Note: AsyncOp object layout
Constant AIO_OP_SIZE as Integer is 64
Constant AIO_OFF_FD as Integer is 0
Constant AIO_OFF_KIND as Integer is 8
Constant AIO_OFF_BUFFER as Integer is 16
Constant AIO_OFF_COUNT as Integer is 24
Constant AIO_OFF_CALLBACK as Integer is 32
Constant AIO_OFF_USERARG as Integer is 40
Constant AIO_OFF_RESULT as Integer is 48
Constant AIO_OFF_LOOP as Integer is 56

Note: Operation kinds stored at AIO_OFF_KIND
Constant AIO_KIND_READ as Integer is 0
Constant AIO_KIND_WRITE as Integer is 1

Note: fcntl commands — F_GETFL fetches the file status flags, F_SETFL sets them
Constant AIO_F_GETFL as Integer is 3
Constant AIO_F_SETFL as Integer is 4

Note: O_NONBLOCK (0x800) — the status flag that makes read/write return instead of block
Constant AIO_O_NONBLOCK as Integer is 2048

Note: epoll readiness masks for the two transfer directions
Constant AIO_EPOLLIN as Integer is 1
Constant AIO_EPOLLOUT as Integer is 4

Note: Status codes returned by the async I/O API
Constant AIO_OK as Integer is 0
Constant AIO_ERR_NULL as Integer is 0 minus 1
Constant AIO_ERR_FCNTL as Integer is 0 minus 2
Constant AIO_ERR_ALLOC as Integer is 0 minus 3

Process called "async_io_set_nonblocking" takes fd as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    A completion-style transfer must never block the reactor thread: when the
    event loop reports a descriptor ready and the dispatcher issues its single
    read or write, that syscall has to return immediately even if a partial or
    spurious readiness leaves nothing to move. Placing the descriptor in
    O_NONBLOCK mode is the precondition that guarantees this, so it is applied
    once at submission time before the descriptor is ever registered.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read the current file status flags with fcntl(fd, F_GETFL, 0). A negative
    return means the descriptor is invalid or the query failed, reported as
    AIO_ERR_FCNTL. Combine the existing flags with O_NONBLOCK using the bitwise
    or operator so no other status bit is disturbed, then install the merged
    mask with fcntl(fd, F_SETFL, flags). A negative set result is likewise
    AIO_ERR_FCNTL; success is AIO_OK.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Exactly two fcntl syscalls, done once per submitted operation on the cold
    setup path. No allocation.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The caller retains ownership of fd; this only alters its status flags. A
    non-zero (negative) status is surfaced rather than silently ignored so a
    bad descriptor cannot be armed into the loop.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let flags be proc linux_x86_64_syscall_fcntl from Sys with fd, AIO_F_GETFL, 0
    If flags is less than 0:
        Return AIO_ERR_FCNTL
    End If

    Let merged be flags bitwise or AIO_O_NONBLOCK
    Let rc be proc linux_x86_64_syscall_fcntl from Sys with fd, AIO_F_SETFL, merged
    If rc is less than 0:
        Return AIO_ERR_FCNTL
    End If
    Return AIO_OK
End Process

Process called "async_read" takes loop as Integer, fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer, callback as Integer, user_arg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Arm a deferred read. The transfer is not performed here; instead the
    descriptor is made non-blocking and registered with the reactor for input
    readiness so that the actual read happens later, exactly when the kernel
    reports data available. All state the deferred completion needs — buffer,
    count, and the caller's callback — is captured in an AsyncOp whose pointer
    the reactor carries as the dispatch argument.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Reject a null loop up front. Put fd in non-blocking mode and abort with the
    fcntl error if that fails. Allocate a 64-byte AsyncOp and populate it with
    the descriptor, kind (read), buffer, count, callback, user_arg, a zero
    initial result, and the owning loop. Register fd with the event loop for
    EPOLLIN, handing the internal dispatcher $async_io_on_ready as the callback
    and the AsyncOp pointer as the user argument. If registration fails, the
    AsyncOp is freed and the loop's error is propagated so nothing leaks.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two fcntl syscalls plus one AsyncOp allocation and one event_loop_add on the
    submission path; the transfer itself costs one syscall later at readiness.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null loop returns AIO_ERR_NULL. The caller owns fd and buffer for the whole
    operation lifetime and must keep them valid until the completion callback
    fires. The dispatcher pointer is a module-internal $name value, so dispatch
    cannot be redirected by the caller.
    @End Security_Scope

    If loop is equal to 0:
        Return AIO_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let nb be async_io_set_nonblocking(fd)
    If nb is less than 0:
        Return nb
    End If

    Let op be proc allocate from Memory with AIO_OP_SIZE
    If op is equal to 0:
        Return AIO_ERR_ALLOC
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_FD, fd
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_KIND, AIO_KIND_READ
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_BUFFER, buffer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_COUNT, count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_CALLBACK, callback
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_USERARG, user_arg
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_RESULT, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_LOOP, loop

    Let rc be proc event_loop_add from EL with loop, fd, AIO_EPOLLIN, $async_io_on_ready, op
    If rc is less than 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with op
        Return rc
    End If
    Return AIO_OK
End Process

Process called "async_write" takes loop as Integer, fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer, callback as Integer, user_arg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Arm a deferred write. Symmetric to async_read: the write is not attempted
    now but registered against output readiness, so the reactor drives the
    single write syscall only when the kernel reports the descriptor writable,
    avoiding any blocking send on a full socket or pipe.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Reject a null loop. Set fd non-blocking, propagating any fcntl failure.
    Allocate and populate a 64-byte AsyncOp with kind (write), buffer, count,
    callback, user_arg, a zero initial result, and the owning loop. Register fd
    for EPOLLOUT with $async_io_on_ready as the callback and the AsyncOp as the
    user argument, unwinding the allocation if registration fails.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two fcntl syscalls, one AsyncOp allocation, and one event_loop_add on the
    submission path; the write itself is a single syscall at readiness.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null loop returns AIO_ERR_NULL. The caller owns fd and buffer and must keep
    the buffer contents valid until completion. Dispatch is fixed to the
    module-internal $async_io_on_ready pointer.
    @End Security_Scope

    If loop is equal to 0:
        Return AIO_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let nb be async_io_set_nonblocking(fd)
    If nb is less than 0:
        Return nb
    End If

    Let op be proc allocate from Memory with AIO_OP_SIZE
    If op is equal to 0:
        Return AIO_ERR_ALLOC
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_FD, fd
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_KIND, AIO_KIND_WRITE
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_BUFFER, buffer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_COUNT, count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_CALLBACK, callback
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_USERARG, user_arg
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_RESULT, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_LOOP, loop

    Let rc be proc event_loop_add from EL with loop, fd, AIO_EPOLLOUT, $async_io_on_ready, op
    If rc is less than 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with op
        Return rc
    End If
    Return AIO_OK
End Process

Process called "async_io_on_ready" takes op as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    The completion engine. This is the internal callback the event loop invokes
    when a registered descriptor becomes ready; its address is taken elsewhere
    in this module as $async_io_on_ready. It converts kernel readiness into a
    finished transfer: perform the operation once, record the outcome, retire
    the registration so the one-shot completion cannot re-fire, hand control to
    the caller's callback, and reclaim the AsyncOp.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    A null op is ignored defensively (return 0). Read fd, kind, buffer, count,
    and the owning loop from the AsyncOp. Dispatch on kind: kind read issues
    linux_x86_64_syscall_read(fd, buffer, count); any other kind is a write via
    linux_x86_64_syscall_write(fd, buffer, count). The syscall return — bytes
    transferred, or a negative errno — is stored at AIO_OFF_RESULT so the
    completion callback can read it through async_io_result. The descriptor is
    then removed from the loop with event_loop_remove (the completion is
    one-shot; leaving it armed would re-enter the dispatcher on a freed op).
    The caller's callback, if present, is invoked via call_indirect_1 with the
    AsyncOp pointer as its single argument, matching the callback ABI. Finally
    the AsyncOp is freed. The callback runs before the free, so it may still
    read result/fd/buffer/count; after this returns the op pointer is dangling.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Exactly one read or write syscall plus one event_loop_remove and one
    deallocate per completion, and a single indirect call into user code. No
    allocation on the completion path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    A null op returns 0 without touching memory. Deregistration happens before
    the user callback and before the free, so a callback cannot observe a
    still-armed descriptor pointing at memory about to be reclaimed. The user
    callback pointer is invoked verbatim per the call_indirect_1 contract; the
    caller supplied it and is responsible for its validity.
    @End Security_Scope

    If op is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let fd be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_FD
    Let kind be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_KIND
    Let buffer be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_BUFFER
    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_COUNT
    Let loop be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_LOOP

    Let transferred be 0
    If kind is equal to AIO_KIND_READ:
        Set transferred to proc linux_x86_64_syscall_read from Sys with fd, buffer, count
    Otherwise:
        Set transferred to proc linux_x86_64_syscall_write from Sys with fd, buffer, count
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_RESULT, transferred

    proc event_loop_remove from EL with loop, fd

    Let cb be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_CALLBACK
    If cb is not equal to 0:
        proc call_indirect_1 from Call with cb, op
    End If

    proc deallocate from Memory with op
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "async_io_result" takes op as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    The completion callback needs the transfer outcome, but the dispatcher frees
    the AsyncOp immediately after the callback returns. This accessor is the
    supported way to read the stored byte count (or negative errno) during the
    callback, keeping the AsyncOp layout private to this module.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Return the value stored at AIO_OFF_RESULT, which the dispatcher writes from
    the read/write syscall return before invoking the callback. A null op yields
    AIO_ERR_NULL so a misuse outside a live completion is distinguishable.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null op returns AIO_ERR_NULL. Valid only while the AsyncOp is live, i.e.
    from within the completion callback before the dispatcher frees it.
    @End Security_Scope

    If op is equal to 0:
        Return AIO_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_RESULT
End Process

Process called "async_io_fd" takes op as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Expose the descriptor associated with an operation so a completion callback
    can correlate the result with the file, socket, or pipe it submitted,
    without reaching into the private AsyncOp layout.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Return the descriptor stored at AIO_OFF_FD. A null op returns AIO_ERR_NULL.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null op returns AIO_ERR_NULL. Pure read of caller-owned descriptor number.
    @End Security_Scope

    If op is equal to 0:
        Return AIO_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_FD
End Process

Process called "async_io_buffer" takes op as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Expose the data buffer pointer so a read completion callback can consume the
    bytes just delivered (and a write completion can identify its source) using
    the transferred count from async_io_result, all without depending on the
    private field offsets.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Return the buffer pointer stored at AIO_OFF_BUFFER. A null op returns 0,
    matching the null-pointer convention for a pointer-valued accessor.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null op returns 0. The buffer is caller-owned; this only returns the
    pointer the caller supplied at submission time.
    @End Security_Scope

    If op is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_BUFFER
End Process

Process called "async_io_count" takes op as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Expose the requested transfer length so a completion callback can compare it
    against the actual bytes moved (async_io_result) to detect short reads or
    short writes and decide whether to resubmit the remainder.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Return the requested count stored at AIO_OFF_COUNT. A null op returns
    AIO_ERR_NULL.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null op returns AIO_ERR_NULL. Pure read.
    @End Security_Scope

    If op is equal to 0:
        Return AIO_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_COUNT
End Process

Process called "async_io_user_arg" takes op as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Expose the caller-supplied context pointer so a completion callback (which
    receives the AsyncOp, not the raw user_arg) can recover the state it needs
    to act on the result. Without this the stored user_arg is unreachable.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Return the user_arg stored at AIO_OFF_USERARG. A null op returns
    AIO_ERR_NULL.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null op returns AIO_ERR_NULL. Pure read.
    @End Security_Scope

    If op is equal to 0:
        Return AIO_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with op, AIO_OFF_USERARG
End Process
